# Script Standards

## Header comment block

Every script must have an overview and usage comment near the top (after the shebang). Follow this structure:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# script-name.sh - One-line description
# ========================================
#
# Description:
#   What this script does and why.
#
# Usage:
#   ./scripts/script-name.sh    # From repo root
#   just recipe-name            # If using justfile
#
# Prerequisites:
#   - Any required tools or conditions
```

## Functions for long scripts

Scripts over ~50 lines must be broken into named functions with a `main()` entry point called at the bottom. Follow the pattern in `install.sh`:

```bash
step_1_do_thing() {
    # What this step accomplishes
    ...
}

step_2_do_other() {
    # What this step accomplishes
    ...
}

main() {
    step_1_do_thing
    step_2_do_other
}

main
```

## Function comments

Every function must have a comment explaining its purpose. One-liners are fine for obvious cases:

```bash
# Returns 0 if the built binary differs from the installed one.
binary_changed() { ... }
```
